es%20began%20to%20rely%20on%20that%20flow%20of%20tips%2C%20Scheherezade%20Rehman%2C%20an%20economist%20and%20professor%20of%20international%20finance%20at%20George%20Washington%20University%2C%20told%20the%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Farticles%2Ftipping-businesses-cant-stop-asking-cc1aca6c%3Fst%3D6ro52nj8dww3i3m%26reflink%3Ddesktopwebshare_permalink%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EWall%20Street%20Journal%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAnd%20now%2C%20businesses%20are%20trying%20to%20avoid%20making%20the%20larger%20wages%20those%20tips%20have%20augmented%20their%20responsibility%2C%20as%20the%20economy%20cools.%20Jonathan%20Morduch%20%E2%80%94%20a%20professor%20of%20public%20policy%20and%20economics%20at%20New%20York%20University%20%E2%80%94%20told%20the%20Wall%20Street%20Journal%20that%20as%20businesses%20prepare%20for%20a%20potential%20recession%2C%20%26quot%3Bthey%20don't%20want%20to%20lock%20into%20higher%20wages.%26quot%3B%20Making%20pay%20reliant%20on%20the%20whims%20of%20tippers%20means%20businesses%20can%20stay%20flexible%2C%20and%20they%20don't%20have%20to%20take%20on%20the%20potential%20risks%20of%20actually%20increasing%20their%20costs.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAs%20Insider's%20Andy%20Kiersz%20and%20Jacob%20Zinkula%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fwhy-is-every-place-asking-for-tips-pay-workers-more-2023-5%5C%22%3Ereported%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Famerica-tips-so-much-hates-it-once-banned-7-states-2023-5%5C%22%3Erise%20of%20tipping%20everywhere%3C%2Fa%3E%20may%20be%20pegged%20to%20workers%20getting%20more%20expensive.%20Wages%20have%20been%20on%20the%20rise%2C%20and%20with%20workers%20feeling%20the%20burn%20of%20inflation%20and%20plenty%20of%20job%20openings%2C%20it's%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fwar-for-talent-national-guard-amazon-wendys-competition-employment-2023-7%5C%22%3Estill%20costly%20to%20compete%20for%20new%20employees%3C%2Fa%3E.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BBusinesses%20are%20being%20squeezed%20and%20hoping%20that%20their%20customers%20will%2C%20in%20effect%2C%20be%20willing%20to%20pay%20more%20on%20a%20voluntary%20basis%2C%26quot%3B%20Laurence%20Kotlikoff%2C%20an%20economics%20professor%20at%20Boston%20University%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fwhy-is-every-place-asking-for-tips-pay-workers-more-2023-5%5C%22%3Epreviously%20told%20Insider%3C%2Fa%3E.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ECurrently%2C%20some%20service%20workers%20are%20subject%20to%20what's%20called%20the%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dol.gov%2Fagencies%2Fwhd%2Fstate%2Fminimum-wage%2Ftipped%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Etipped%20minimum%20wage%3C%2Fa%3E.%20That%20wage%20is%20%242.13%2C%20far%20below%20the%20federal%20minimum%20wage%20of%20%247.25%20an%20hour%2C%20and%20means%20that%20paychecks%20are%20primarily%20driven%20by%20the%20tips%20workers%20receive%2C%20rather%20than%20an%20hourly%20rate.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BBusinesses%20are%20happy%20to%20let%20workers%20earn%20more%20from%20tips%2C%20especially%20when%20there's%20no%20pressure%20to%20raise%20the%20tipped%20minimum%2C%26quot%3B%20Morduch%20told%20the%20Wall%20Street%20Journal.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBut%20making%20workers'%20pay%20essentially%20contingent%20on%20customers'%20generosity%20%E2%80%94%20some%20of%20whom%20might%20be%20in%20a%20similar%20work%20situation%2C%20or%20also%20feeling%20the%20sting%20of%20increased%20costs%20%E2%80%94%20likely%20isn't%20a%20viable%20long-term%20strategy.%20The%20Fed%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fwill-there-be-a-recession-federal-reserve-no-longer-predicts-2023-7%2F%5C%22%3Edoesn't%20think%20businesses'%20fears%20of%20a%20recession%20will%20come%20true%3C%2Fa%3E.%20Customers%20are%20getting%20fed%20up%20with%20offloaded%20costs%2C%20and%2C%20even%20in%20a%20slightly%20cooling%20labor%20mark